<div id="stitle" style="display:none;">Notebook Entry</div>
<dl id="n54140c"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="n54" href="#n54140c">N54 (VI.B.45)</a>:  <a href="../../FF/fnbs/n54all.htm#n54140c"> 140(c)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> Zitella&apos;s ritournela</blockquote> <dd class="well"> <blockquote class="sources"> <p class="set">Charming <mark>Zitella</mark>, why shoulds&apos;t thou care? <br>Night is not darker than thy raven hair, <br>And whose bright eyes if the Brigand should see, <br>Thou art the robber, the captive is he; <br>Gentle Zitella banish thy fear; <br>Love&apos;s <mark>Ritornella</mark> tarry and hear.</p> <small> Sigmund Spaeth, <a name="REAW2" href="../../FF/fdra/fdex.htm#REAW2"><cite title="source">Read 'Em and Weep</cite></a> (1935) [Love&apos;s Ritornella] 19</small></blockquote> <mm class="note">Note: A song of English-Irish origin, words by Planche and music by Tom Cooke of Dublin, is typical of the sentimentally romantic songs of the early nineteenth century, and tells of Massaroni the Masher Bandit [sic]. </mm> </dd></dl>
